prompt:
We read a barcode wedge over a serial line and the bytes arrive in bursts while the uploader drains at its own pace, so I want a small byte queue between the two: a fixed-capacity ring buffer in C. Two new files, ringbuf.h and ringbuf.c. C17, nothing beyond string.h/stddef.h -- and specifically no malloc: the caller hands in the storage.

The header must define exactly this struct and API:

    typedef struct {
        unsigned char *buf;   /* caller's storage, cap bytes */
        size_t cap;
        size_t head;          /* index of the oldest byte */
        size_t count;         /* bytes currently stored */
        size_t high;          /* largest count ever seen */
    } ringbuf;

    int    rb_init(ringbuf *rb, void *storage, size_t cap);
    size_t rb_write(ringbuf *rb, const void *src, size_t n);
    size_t rb_read(ringbuf *rb, void *dst, size_t n);
    size_t rb_peek(const ringbuf *rb, void *dst, size_t n);
    size_t rb_len(const ringbuf *rb);
    size_t rb_avail(const ringbuf *rb);
    size_t rb_high(const ringbuf *rb);
    void   rb_clear(ringbuf *rb);

Semantics -- the parts that have bitten us before, spelled out:

- rb_init: 0 on success; -1 if storage is NULL or cap is 0. The caller owns the storage for the ring's whole life; the ring never allocates or frees anything.
- Full vs empty is decided by the count field, not by burning a slot: a ring with cap 8 really stores 8 bytes. head is the read position; new bytes land at (head + count) % cap.
- rb_write appends up to n bytes and returns how many it accepted: min(n, free space). A partial write keeps the FRONT of src and drops the tail -- never a hole, never the suffix. Writing to a full ring returns 0 and changes nothing.
- rb_read copies out up to n of the oldest bytes in arrival order and returns how many it removed: min(n, count). Empty ring: returns 0.
- rb_peek is rb_read without the consuming -- same bytes, same return value, count untouched.
- Data wraps around the end of the storage transparently; order stays strictly first-in first-out across the seam, for reads and peeks alike.
- Bytes are bytes: 0x00 and 0xFF pass through unmangled, nothing in here is a C string.
- rb_len is the stored count, rb_avail is cap minus that.
- rb_high is the high-water mark: the largest count the ring has ever reached (we use it to size the buffer on the next board rev). It only ever ratchets up. rb_clear drops count to 0 -- nothing to read, all space free -- but does NOT reset high.
- n == 0 on any call is a no-op that returns 0.
- No globals, no statics holding state: two rings on the same board must not interfere.

Worked example so there is no ambiguity, cap = 8, fresh ring:

    rb_write "abcdef" (n=6)      -> returns 6, len 6
    rb_read  into out, n=4       -> returns 4, out "abcd", len 2
    rb_write "ghijk" (n=5)       -> returns 5, len 7   (this one wraps)
    rb_read  into out, n=8       -> returns 7, out "efghijk", len 0
    rb_write "0123456789" (n=10) -> returns 8, len 8, avail 0
    rb_write "x" (n=1)           -> returns 0

`make test` is the acceptance gate; Makefile, mintest.h and test_ringbuf.c are fixed.
